column1: Rule 1: Modifiers containing an aromatic carboxylic acid group with ortho or para-positioned amino groups tend to result in a high yield.
column2: Rule 2: Modifiers with amino acids or derivatives that have aromatic side chains, such as phenyl or indole groups, tend to result in a high yield.
column3: Rule 3: Modifiers with multiple hydroxyl groups in close proximity, such as vicinal diols or polyols, tend to result in a high yield.
column4: Rule 4: Modifiers with electron-withdrawing groups such as nitro groups on an aromatic ring tend to result in a high yield.
column5: Rule 5: Modifiers with long aliphatic chains without additional functional groups tend to result in a low yield.
column6: Rule 6: Modifiers with ether linkages and no additional coordinating groups tend to result in a low yield.
column7: Rule 7: Modifiers with a high degree of fluorination tend to result in a low yield.
column8: Rule 8: Modifiers with ketone groups on an aliphatic chain tend to result in a low yield.
column9: Rule 9: Modifiers with pyridine rings without additional functional groups tend to result in a low yield.
column10: Rule 10: Modifiers with formyl groups on an aromatic ring tend to result in a low yield.
column11: Rule 11: Modifiers with a combination of aromatic rings and sulfanyl groups tend to result in a high yield.
column12: Rule 12: Modifiers with a pyridine ring and an additional carboxylic acid group tend to result in a high yield.
column13: Rule 13: Modifiers with a benzofuran structure and additional carboxylic acid groups tend to result in a high yield.
column14: Rule 14: Modifiers with a combination of electron-donating and electron-withdrawing groups on an aromatic ring tend to result in a high yield.
column15: Rule 15: Modifiers with an aromatic ring and a hydroxyl group in the para position tend to result in a high yield.
